[16:07:17] {"event": "tool_call", "tool": "think", "args": {"thought": "\nAnalyzing the 3 failing issues:\n\n**Issue 1 & 5: TC-83232 Newsletter (chromium + edge)**\n- Selector: `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]`\n- The incremental scrolling loop is running but the element never becomes visible in 30s (waitFor timeout)\n- The loop scrolls in viewport-height increments but on UAT the Builder.io lazy sections may need a different approach\n- The test already has a complex loop — but the final `waitFor` on line 414 is timing out at 30_000ms. Wait... looking at the code again:\n  - Line 414: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n  - But line 464 has: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 45_000 });`\n  - The error says line 414 which is inside the step. Looking at the stack trace again:\n    - `at /Users/virginia.zambudio/PlaywrightAutomation/tests/home-page.spec.ts:414:49`\n  - So there's a different version of the test than what I see currently (the code currently at 464 seems updated). The current test has 45_000 timeout at 464 and the failing stack trace says line 414 with 30_000 timeout. The failing tests seem to be from an older run. But the user says \"FIx this issues\" so we need to fix the current code.\n\nWait - the error message says `timeout: 30000ms` at line 414. But the current code at line 414 shows `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });` - checking the offset. The view showed line 414: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`. So there IS a 30_000 at 414 AND a 45_000 at 464 (after the loop).\n\nLooking more carefully at the test code structure:\n- Line 409: step 'Scroll to footer newsletter form'\n- Line 414: FIRST waitFor with 30_000 - this is an EARLY check inside the scrolling step BEFORE the loop\n- Line 464: FINAL waitFor with 45_000 - this is AFTER the loop\n\nWait let me re-read. Line 413 shows:\n```\nawait page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));\n> 414 |             await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });\n```\nBut the current code at lines 413-464 is the INCREMENTAL loop version. Hmm, the error context shows an older version of the test (simple scroll + 30_000 timeout). The current file may already have the incremental loop. But the user is saying \"fix these issues\" which were observed in a recent run.\n\nActually the error message in the prompt shows the STACK TRACE from the failing run. The stack trace says line 414. But when I view the file, line 414 shows something different. The user's \"Additional Instructions\" are describing failures from a recent test run. The errors happen at line 414 per the stack trace. Current line 414 reads:\n`await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n\nWait, let me re-read the view output. The view file showed:\n- Line 412: `// element to mount before interacting.` (from the error in the prompt)\n- Line 413: `await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));`\n- Line 414: `await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n\nBut what I got from viewing lines 390-469 of home-page.spec.ts shows a different version starting at 409. So the test has ALREADY been refactored in the current file but the errors shown in the prompt are from a PRIOR run with the old code.\n\nActually wait - let me reread what I got from the view. Lines 409-465 show the incremental scroll loop version. That means the current file HAS the loop. The error in the prompt came from the PRIOR run before this refactoring. But the user says \"fix this issues\" - these are failures from the most recent run.\n\nHmm. Actually, looking at the test at line 413/414, the error in the prompt shows the SIMPLE version (just one scroll + waitFor). But the CURRENT file (which I read) shows the LOOP version.\n\nSo there are two possibilities:\n1. The test was already partially fixed (loop added) but is still failing\n2. The error is from the old version\n\nThe user's prompt says these are issues that need fixing NOW, and the code has already been updated. Maybe the loop version still fails. Let me check what the current line 414 has:\n\nFrom view output lines 409-465:\n- 409: `await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {`\n- 413: (comment line)\n- 414: (empty line or part of loop)\n\nActually looking at the view more carefully:\nLine 413: `await page.evaluate(() => window.scrollTo(0, document.body.scrollHeight));`\nThat contradicts what I see in the view which shows `// The newsletter section is Builder.io-driven...`\n\nI think there's a mismatch. The error stack traces in the prompt show the OLD version (simple scroll at line 413 + waitFor at 414), but the current file has been updated to the incremental loop.\n\nBUT - the user says to fix the issues listed. The errors in the prompt are from the most recent test run (as the `## Additional Instructions` context). So the old code is still there OR the loop was added but still fails.\n\nI need to re-read more carefully. Let me look at what lines 409-415 actually say in the current file.\n\nFrom the view I got lines 390-469:\n- Line 413: `await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {`  \n- Line 414 in the error corresponds to inside this step\n\nActually the offset shown is the actual line numbers from the file. Line 409 in the actual file says:\n`await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {`\n\nAnd line 414 says:\n`await homePage.newsletterEmailInput.waitFor({ state: 'visible', timeout: 30_000 });`\n\nBut from my view output at line 413, it says:\n`await test.step('Navigate to homepage', async () => {`\n\nThere's confusion because the view output line numbers ARE the actual file line numbers. Let me re-read:\n\nFrom view starting at offset 390:\n- 409: `await test.step('Navigate to homepage', async () => {`\n- 410: `    await homePage.navigate(homePageData.urls.home);`  \n- 411: `});`\n- 412: (empty)\n- 413: `await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {`\n- 414: `    // The newsletter section is Builder.io-driven...`\n\nWait no, the actual output shows:\n```\n413:         await test.step('Scroll to footer newsletter form', async () => {\n414:             // The newsletter section is Builder.io-driven and is only rendered\n```\n\nSo line 414 is a comment. But the error says line 414 has `waitFor`. \n\nOH - I think the error message in the prompt is from an OLDER run before the code was updated. The current file already has the improved version. The issue is that the USER SAYS these failures happened and wants them fixed - but the code may STILL be failing for different reasons.\n\nActually the most sensible interpretation: the user is providing the errors from the most recent run, and the current code I'm viewing is what's actually in the file right now. The mismatch in line numbers means the current file has DIFFERENT code from what generated those errors. So the errors are from the old code before recent fixes.\n\nI should investigate the CURRENT state of the code and understand if the failing tests are likely to still fail.\n\nFor TC-83232 (newsletter):\n- Current code has the complex incremental scroll loop — this is more robust\n- But the selector `div.bg-primary input[type=\"email\"]` may simply not match on UAT\n- The actual issue might be that Builder.io lazy loads the newsletter and the selector is wrong\n\nFor TC-83240 (wishlist authenticated):\n- Error: login page email input not visible (timeout 15_000)\n- `input[name=\"email\"][type=\"email\"]` not visible after navigating to `/myaccount`\n- Current LoginPage navigates to `/auth/login` with 45_000 timeout\n- The current code already handles this with 45_000 timeout and body click\n- Error shows old 15_0